TY  - JOUR
AU  - Rass, N.
TI  - Policies and strategies to address the vulnerability of pastoralists in sub-Saharan Africa.
T2  - PPLPI Working Paper - Pro-Poor Livestock Policy Initiative, FAO
M3  - Bulletin
AB  - This paper makes a case for increased policy attention to pastoralists in Sub-Saharan Africa (SSA). The paper presents estimates of the numbers of agro-pastoral populations globally, their livestock and their contribution to national economies as well as of the incidence of poverty. Out of the estimated 120 million agro-pastoralists worldwide, 50 million live in SSA, mainly in West and East Africa, where they are estimated to produce around 33 and 41% of total ruminant meat respectively. Poverty incidence among pastoralists is high, ranging from 25 to 55%. This paper examines the causes and dynamics of poverty among pastoral populations in Africa drawing on the sustainable livelihoods framework with a focus on vulnerability to shocks. Traditional livelihood and risk management strategies appear to be increasingly ineffective and pastoralists, progressively more vulnerable to droughts, market exclusion, epidemics and violent conflicts, as well as being negatively affected by increasing human and livestock pressure on fragile drylands. The key policy question identified is, whether it is preferable to invest in pastoral development or whether it is more appropriate to support exit-strategies for pastoralists. It is argued that these should be complementary strategies. On the one hand, pastoralism is the best, if not the only, means to make productive and sustainable use of natural resources in arid and semi-arid areas while on the other hand, increasing human and livestock pressure in the drylands, needs to be addressed by strategies that support the adoption of alternative income generation activities by some agro-pastoral people. The final part of the paper examines some policy options to sustain pastoral development. The main focus is on policies mitigating the vulnerability of pastoral people to shocks. The review of policy responses by various countries in SSA shows some interesting and innovative approaches. Kenya provides an example of effective drought management policies and of how pastoral people can capitalize on market opportunities. Chad illustrates the cost-effectiveness of combining animal and human health service delivery to pastoral people in remote areas. Tanzania provides an example of the incorporation of specific pastoral livelihood and employment promotion issues into the national employment policy. Decision-makers are however urged to continue experimenting and to refine and adapt policies to the specific features of the different pastoral situations.
