T2  - South Asian Anthropologist
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Tribals form an integral part of forest environment. They depend on plants for food, shelter and medicine. Tribals make their livelihood on minor forest produce collection and marketing them. The massive and rapid deforestation not only placed the livelihood of tribals in danger, but also is responsible for ecological disasters such as flash floods, soil erosion, climatic changes, drought and famine. It has been observed that deforestation effects are reflected on indigenous herbal drugs of India in general and ethno-medicine of tribal communities in particular. The problems of poor primitive tribals who still do not have an access to modern health care facilities are compounded by deforestation. This paper highlights negative effects of deforestation on the overall medicinal flora and livelihood of tribals living in the Visakha agency area of Andhra Pradesh (A.P). It also examines how deforestation caused a decline in the both herbal medical practices and the roles of local healers namely Guruvuor Goravagaduin the native health care system of these tribes called DisariVaidyam. It analysis various factors as to how medicinal plants cultivation, conservation and propagation would help and improve on the health status of tribes.
