AU  - Rai, A.
AU  - Bhowmick, M. K.
AU  - Singh, H. B.
TI  - Micronutrient seed priming: a potential tool in integrated nutrient management.
T2  - SATSA Mukhaptra Annual Technical Issue
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Low input oriented production of crop species in eastern part of India gets affected by drought, poor crop establishment and low availability of macro- and micronutrients. Although soil and foliar applications are the most prevalent methods of micronutrient addition, the cost involved and difficulty in obtaining high quality micronutrient fertilizers are major concerns in developing countries. Micronutrient seed treatments, which include seed priming and seed coating, are attractive and easy alternatives. Seed priming has been found to improve crop establishment and to increase crop yields under low input management or marginal soil conditions. Seed priming with nutrients can increase plant growth and nutrient uptake, and improve water use efficiency of several crop species. Thus, seed priming can be a solution as an easy and cost-effective method to increase crop yield in marginalized areas for the resource-poor farmers, where other resources are hardly available or limited.
