TI  - Soil management: the basic requirement of organic farming.
T2  - Advances in organic farming
M3  - Book chapter
AB  - Organic farming is characterized by the use of natural processes and inputs to promote soil health and ecological unit services. A growing body of scientific literature proposes that the soil management approaches used in organic farming enhance general soil health, but little has been studied on the exact techniques used to build healthy soils over time. In an attempt to address the water scarcity affecting the resource-poor farmers and home-gardeners in the Eastern Cape of South Africa, an agricultural extension pilot project was designed as an intervention to address the challenge of both drought and poor soil quality. The approach was two-pronged, in that the project targeted both resource-poor households and students of the Agricultural Extension Honours programme, with students participating as part of their extension outreach experiential learning. The programme was infused with pragmatic pedagogical knowledge and a strong skills development component, designed to equip the Agricultural Extension graduates with the knowledge and skills that would most benefit local resource-poor household gardeners. Results showed that cabbage fertilized with animal-based liquid fertilizers flourished, developing a profuse growth of new, shiny leaves, and that with an enhanced, more efficient use of scarce water, fewer weeds and pests were observed. Therefore, liquid organic fertilizers could be used as an alternative to the direct application of cow manure on the vegetable garden, since it has multiple advantages, forming a means of irrigation and soil enrichment at the same time.
