AU  - Cruz, J.
AU  - Piniero, M.
AU  - Pezo, D.
TI  - Participatory evaluation of pastures with criteria of small and medium livestock producers.
T2  - Pastos y Forrajes
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This paper presents a participatory approach using farmers' knowledge in evaluating improved pastures in EL Chal, Peten, Guatemala. On-farm experiments of 5 improved pastures selected by farmers were conducted in farmers' fields to determine the local criteria for pasture evaluation. Two evaluations based on seasonal changes were undertaken to determine if farmers' indicators would vary. Farmers' evaluations were tabulated and compared using economic variables, particularly land tenancy (private owner and leaseholder). Both groups of farmers used a number of criteria in evaluating improved pastures, including animal preference, resistance to dry period and pests, and competitive ability against weeds, among others. The farmers' indicators remained approximately the same in the 2 seasons, but the ranking of categories varied. During the first evaluation, farmers emphasized indicators that are observable (colour and vigour), while during the second evaluation, they focused more on the pastures' overall performance (resistance to limiting factors). The biophysical components of the production system and the socio-economic condition of the farmers affected their evaluation. Farmers whose farms were located in undulated area gave more importance on tolerance of drought and ability to grow in sloping areas, while those who had farms in flat areas emphasized resistance to pests and waterlogging, and shade tolerance. Small-scale farmers tended to focus on the pasture's ability to compete with weeds, while this is not that important for medium-scale producers. Taking into consideration culturally significant indicators can facilitate the implementation of projects and the transfer of technologies that people can identify with and use within their limited environment.
