TI  - Postharvest-losses affect the sustainable production of onions and tomatoes in the Nigerian savannah.
T2  - Proceedings of the International Conference on Postharvest Technology and Quality Management in Arid Tropics, Sultanate of Oman, 31 January-2 February, 2005
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - Onions (Allium cepaL.) and tomatoes (Lycopersicon esculentumMill.) are predominant crops in the semi-arid guinea, sudan and sahel savannah regions of northern Nigeria. More than 60% of the cultivated crops are produced by subsistence farmers in non-irrigated rain-fed fields under moisture stress with seasonal droughts. Under the prevailing conditions, postharvest losses are quite significant. This paper examines how postharvest losses are linked to sustainable production of onions and tomatoes in the Nigerian savannah. It is observed that farmers respond to increasing losses of their products negatively. Losses are tied to price hike, which in turn is tied to decreasing demand and consequent farmer apathy towards increased production. Efforts at reducing postharvest losses significantly raised the production level due to increased farmer input occasioned by higher product demand. It is concluded that sustainable production of these crops is achievable with proper implementation of effective postharvest loss prevention strategies.
