AU  - ,
AU  - ,
TI  - Moving herds to moving markets. Creating profitable markets for African pastoralists.
T2  - Des troupeaux en mouvement vers des marches en mouvement: creer des marches profitables pour les eleveurs africains
M3  - Book
AB  - In Africa, pastoralists produce much of the meat and milk and form an important, but underappreciated, part of the economy of many African countries. However, they face considerable difficulties when trying to sell their products. Indeed, they are scattered over huge arid grazing areas, lacking the roads, infrastructure and basic services that farmers in more favored areas consider perfectly normal. Many move from place to place in search of pasture and water, making it difficult to provide them with the services they need. With few market outlets, they have little incentive to improve their production. Repeated episodes of drought can force pastoralists in an entire region to resort to outside help. So how can markets for pastoralist products be improved and pastoralists overcome the vicious cycle of poverty? This book presents a number of solutions. Drawing on 15 cases in nine countries (Benin, Botswana, Burkina Faso, Ethiopia, Kenya, Mali, Niger, Tanzania and Uganda), it identifies four key characteristics of pastoralism in Africa (mobility, extensive grazing, common land use and local breeds). It presents the challenges and opportunities in the marketing of live animals, meat, milk and leather products. It discusses the best ways to ensure that livestock keepers have the inputs they need to produce efficiently: animal health, feeds, breeds and husbandry. It investigates the services necessary for the proper functioning of the marketing chain: market information, financial services, transport, markets, processing infrastructure and quality control. It examines three aspects related to the skills and organization needed to make pastoral markets work: capacity building, organization and gender issues. Finally, it makes recommendations for government and donor policies, and indicates priority areas for development initiatives aimed at improving marketing. Throughout, the book not only focuses on pastoralists, but also on other actors in the livestock value chains, such as traders, processors such as slaughterhouses and dairies, as well as service providers such as financial institutions, advisory services, government and development organizations.
