AU  - Poultouchidou, A.
AU  - Avagyan, A.
AU  - Tapio-Bistrom, M. L.
AU  - Bernoux, M.
TI  - Planning, implementing and evaluating climate-smart agriculture in smallholder farming systems.
T2  - Mitigation of Climate Change in Agriculture Series (MICCA)
M3  - Bulletin
AB  - The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO), with financial support from the Government of Finland, designed the Mitigation of Climate Change in Agriculture (MICCA) Programme to build climate-smart agriculture (CSA) readiness. The programme was also established to demonstrate that ongoing agricultural development programmes could bring co-benefits in terms of climate change adaptation and mitigation thereby increasing the uptake of CSA at significantly larger scale. The MICCA CSA pilot projects (2011-2014), implemented jointly with partners in Kenya and the United Republic of Tanzania, promoted integrated and diversified farming systems and agro-ecological principles. The pilot projects linked research activities, practical work in farmers' fields and policy making at different levels to enhance the effectiveness of planning and programming for CSA on farms, throughout the landscape and at the national level. The pilot projects were implemented in an integrated crop-livestock-tree farming system in Kaptumo, Kenya and a cereal-based upland farming system in Kolero in the United Republic of Tanzania. They were specifically designed to: (1) promote an exchange of knowledge between farmers, extension agents and scientists with a view to identifying, developing and promoting an integrated package of CSA practices and technologies; (2) conduct scientific research to assess the GHG emission fluxes and mitigation potential of farming practices and identify synergies and trade-offs; and (3) analyse the barriers to adoption of CSA and the benefits it can deliver in order to advance the scaling up of CSA, through extension, policy support and investments. Some results of the MICCA pilot studies are as follows: (i) farmers who participated in the MICCA pilot projects reported that the main benefits of following the CSA approach resulted in higher yields, raised farm income and increased food availability; (ii) scenarios, modelling and measurements serve an important role in evaluating and prioritizing CSA practices for implementation and scaling up; and (iii) bringing sound, up-to-date evidence into decision-making processes can help shape policy making that effectively supports CSA. A number of recommendations regarding CSA, particularly the implementation of CSA at the local level, are presented.
