AU  - Sodany, T.
AU  - Poungchompu, S.
TI  - Factors affecting agricultural land use of smallholder farmers in Ouheng village, Cambodia.
T2  - Proceedings, International Conference on Interdisciplinary Research and Development (ICIRD), 29-31 October 2015, Maejo University, Chiang Mai, Thailand
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - As concerns over struggle for agricultural land use in Northeastern Cambodia are increasing, smallholder farmers are then becoming highly affected by household's characteristics, local biological components, training and extension visits. In consequence, these issues prompt a mixed qualitative and quantitative-based research to be conducted, aiming (1) to study characteristics of agricultural land use for smallholder farmers; and (2) to identify factors affecting agricultural land use for smallholder farmers in Ouheng village of Cambodia. This research was carried out by purposive sampling of 30 respondents who were holding land less than 3 hectares, as well as some key informants representing relevant institutions. Two focus-group discussions were conducted with 10 persons in each group. This study was based on the household survey in 2015 using applied descriptive statistics and Chis-square test run by SPSS version 16 in which Chi-square test was use to find the relationship by comparing between two groups that one group referred to farmers have change in crop pattern while the other group have not changed. The finding indicates a number of affecting factors of land use by small-scale farmers were local biological components, Socioeconomic, access to credit, technological conditions in which local biological components comprised of local climate, weather, and land type with soil fertility and land connected to infrastructure. Socio-economic and technological conditions include labor availability, age of household heads, decision maker training and extension visits. Another assumption reveals that land use by small-scale farmers in Ouheng village was 1.5 hectares on average per household dominated by paddy fields and followed by cassava. The cassava cultivated area has increased significantly by 21.92% in 2015 due to the fact that the prices and market access were favorable to farmers together with private companies provided incentive and promotion. The new crop variety could be high capacity to tolerance the drought and resist to disease together with improving of agricultural skills as well as crop management technique through development of comprehensive training and regular extension visits.
