TY  - JOUR
AU  - Aparna Gupta, Aparna Gupta
AU  - Kaushal, J. R.
TI  - Evaluation of feeding practices in crossbred cattle by progressive dairy farmers of Punjab - an on-farm study.
T2  - Indian Journal of Animal Sciences
M3  - Journal article
AB  - An on-farm study was conducted to evaluate the feeding schedule of crossbred cows, maintained by a progressive dairy farmer. 12 selected animals were divided into mid, early and late lactation groups of 4 animals each. During the study period between May and September, the environmental temperature ranged between 34 and 41°C (max.) and 20 and 28°C (min) and relative humidity was between 4 and 83%. Comparison between the nutrients offered and those required as per NRC standards revealed a great discrepancy. The level of feeding (%) by the farmer during early, mid and late lactation groups were 131,114 and 120 for DM; 120, 109 and 107 for TDN; 115, 104 and 105 for ME; 92, 91 and 81 for RDP; 119, 115 and 140 for UDP; 156, 144 and 185 for Ca; and 267, 265 and 285 for P, respectively, of that of requirement by NRC, 1988. High intake of nutrients and DM was adding to the heat stress discomfort during the months of June to August when the RH was 70 to 80% and maximum temperature of 345°C. Modifications (reducing the EE content of concentrate mixture, reducing DM intake, urea incorporation and raising the level of feeding of concentrate) were made in the feeding schedule and a test trial with 10 animals (5 animals in test and 5 in control group) was performed with minimal changes in all other factors (stages of lactation, season, fodder type) and it was observed that the animals under test group produced 19.03 kg milk in comparison to 16.80 kg in the start of the test period, i.e. an increase of 2.24 kg/animal/d (13.3%). In the 5th week while there was a drop of 800 g in milk production over that of the previous week production in the control group, the drop in test group was only 180 g/animal/day. There was an increase of Rs 12.33 in income/animal/d. Interestingly, this income increased to Rs 16.43 during week 5 when the animals in the control group were more affected by the heat stress than those in the test group.
