TI  - An empirical analysis on farmers' demand for forest insurance based on forest disasters: a case study of Fujian, Jiangxi, Hunan and Shaanxi provinces.
T2  - World Forestry Research
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Forest insurance plays an evident role in dispersing the management risks of forest farmers and expanding forest financing scale. The study made an empirical analysis of farmers' demand for forest insurance by using the 647 investigation data in Jiangxi, Hunan, Shaanxi and Fujian provinces and by adopting the Logistic model to do the regression analysis of the factors (including natural disasters) leading farmers to buy forest insurance. The result of regression indicated that: the variables included in the model, i.e., forest disasters, educational background, physical status, the number of migrant workers, the number of family members, forest land area, the proportion of forest income in household income, and the participation in forestry cooperatives, had significantly different impacts on the demand for forest insurance in different provinces, while Fujian and Hunan were the two provinces where forest disasters had significant influences on households' demand for forest insurance.
