TI  - Extension strategy to reach the un-reached farmers.
T2  - Current Biotica
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Majority of the un-reached farmers were middle aged with illiteracy, had medium farming experience, belonged to scheduled castes and scheduled tribes, under nuclear family with medium family size, living in thatched houses, agriculture and agricultural labour as their occupation, had poor social contact, small and marginal farmers with medium annual income, low material possession, medium achievement motivation, management orientation, self confidence, risk orientation, and extent of risk in terms of money. Under personal factors, 'illiteracy', under economic, 'low size of holding', under social, 'backward caste/low caste', under geographical, 'poor transport facilities' under technological, 'lack of irrigation facilities' under environmental, 'severe and continuous drought conditions' under marketing, 'exploitation of farmers by traders' under transfer of technology, 'Poor contact of extension staff' under administrative factors, 'lack of crop insurance' were ranked first by the un-reached farmers for their un-reachedness. The strategy was divided in to five broad areas Viz., 'Education' as the primary concern followed by 'Reoriented extension activities', 'Economic concern', 'Technological concern' and 'Socio-psychological concern'. An appropriate and feasible model was designed to reach the un-reached farmers. This strategy will help the administrators, policy makers and other personnel who are working in the field of agricultural extension in executing the extension programmes towards the objective of sustainable agriculture.
