TI  - Irrigation planning for Harpur (Pusa) village.
T2  - Journal of Research, Birsa Agricultural University
M3  - Journal article
AB  - One hundred farmers in Bihar, India, were selected randomly for survey on the basis of probability proportion to the number of proportions falling under marginal, small, medium and large category. The agricultural practices popular among the farmers of the village particularly in reference to irrigation were studied and analysed. Keeping in view the affinity of the villagers, social and natural constraints and interests of the beneficiaries a suitable irrigation plan was proposed to uplift the socioeconomic status of the beneficiaries and improve the productivity of land. The study revealed that majority of farmers (57.0%) were marginal farmers. Most of the farmers fall in the category of low-income group. The literacy level of the farmers was quite high (73%) and most of the farmers (60%) have large size (above 8 members) families. Though, the farmers were eager to adopt advanced technology of irrigation water management but were totally unaware. It was suggested that wild flooding method of irrigation should be replaced by check basin method. To provide life saving irrigations to all the crops a minimum of 63 shallow tube wells must be installed in addition to 45 tube wells which are there at present. The proposed irrigation plan may give an additional net return of Rs. 23.9 lakh per annum against a recurring investment of Rs. 32.80 lakh per annum towards irrigation and fertilizer costs with an increase in production of about 1800 metric tonnes.
