AU  - Nadeem Shah, Nadeem Shah
AU  - Ranjeet Verma, Ranjeet Verma
AU  - Verma, U. K.
AU  - Dewry, R. K.
TI  - Effect of heat stress on reproduction in dairy animals.
T2  - Journal of Experimental Zoology, India
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Livestock sector plays a pivotal role for livelihood food security in India. The major income sources to the farmers are animal husbandry and agriculture that directly have impact on economic conditions of the farmers. One of the major threats to the sustainability of the livestock is the changes in the climate. Extremities in climate and seasonal fluctuations in herbage quantity and quality affect the well-being of livestock and leads to decline in production and reproduction efficiency. Climate change influences the water demand, availability and quality. Changes in temperature and weather may affect the quality, quantity and distribution of rainfall, snow melt, river flow and groundwater. Heat stress has direct and indirect effects on health performance of animals leading to changes in physiology, metabolism, hormonal and immune system. Genetic Selection and production of thermo tolerant animals will improve the economic status of dairy farmers. Environmental stress adversely affects the production, reproduction and health of animal through physiological changes. The most common method to reduce heat stress in dairy cows by using cooling system such that provision of shades, sprinklers, ventilation and evaporative cooling will be suitable for adapting to climates changes.
