TY  - JOUR
AU  - Wolf, Benjamin
TI  - Climate protection in the food industry.
T2  - Ernahrung
M3  - Journal article
AB  - With the exception of a few locations, climate change will result in increased strain on land and water while decreasing crop growth. Due to the effects of climate change on stock productivity and fish migration patterns, productivity is predicted to decline for nearly half of the world's fisheries. The tropics will be the most negatively impacted, along with OECD fisheries. Farmers, aquaculture producers, and fishermen will face growing pressure to change their methods and technology as a result of these difficulties over time. In spite of the fact that there is a lot that individuals can do on their own, in the worst-case scenarios, government regulations will be crucial for successful climate change adaptation. The OECD is currently investigating how inclusive and scientifically informed policy-making processes may best assist the adoption and implementation of necessary policies such as disaster recovery and catastrophic insurance as well as policies to improve co-operation, preparedness, and resilience. Since energy, transportation, and other industrial sectors have gotten more focus in GHG mitigation efforts than the food industry, by the middle of the century, emissions from agriculture may overtake them as the main source of emissions worldwide. Therefore, without the industry doing its part to combat climate change, it will be impossible to reach the Paris Agreement's targets to restrict global temperature increases to 1.5°C or well below 2 degrees Celsius. The OECD's work identifies policy measures that can maximize food production's ability to mitigate climate change while minimizing its negative economic effects on the agri-food industry and consumers. To prevent merely moving carbon emissions from one place to another, policies at the international, national, and sector levels must cooperate. All of this must be done in low-income countries.
