TI  - How do neglected and underutilised crops (NUCS) in Africa contribute to food security, nutrition and climate change outcomes: a scoping review protocol.
T2  - agriRxiv
M3  - Preprint
AB  - Building a more resilient food system requires growing crops that are adapted to variable environments- more heat, less moisture, greater pressure from pests and diseases, frequent extreme weather conditions like droughts and floods, inherently weak structured soils. Historically, plant breeding investments have been highly concentrated in cash crops and major staple crops like maise, wheat, and rice. Plant breeding investment in Africa has largely focused on the most economically important crops, like maise, tobacco, cotton, coffee, and cocoa, although some attention has been paid to legumes (including, cowpea and bambara groundnuts). Crops such as millets (i.e., sorghum, fonio, finger and pearl millets), which are utilised and most adapted to smallholder farmer's conditions, have not received as much investment as staple crops. According to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), Sub-Saharan Africa (SSA) is one of the global regions with the least adaptive capacity to climate change. Current climate change predictions for the region paint a scenario of rising temperatures, increased variability in rainfall (change in patterns, onset and amounts) and increased frequency of extreme weather events such as drought, heat, combined drought and heat and floods. It is already experiencing some of these weather extremes with drought and floods ravaging most of SSA's landscape. Agricultural production is of particular concern. Small-scale producers in low- and middle-income countries are among those whose livelihoods are most vulnerable to climate change (Davis et al., 2022). The number of poor people dependent on agriculture and food systems in low- and lower-middle income countries is large-nearly 3.2 billion people live in rural areas, and most still depend to varying degrees on agriculture and food systems for their livelihoods (Lipper et al., 2020). Most of SSA's economies are still heavily dependent (directly or indirectly) on agriculture as a driver of economic and rural development. This is of great concern when viewed within the context of the impacts climate change will have on agriculture, and the vulnerability of rural households and the urban poor, regarding food and nutrition security, because the incidence of crop failure will likely increase. A healthy diet - one that prevents multi-nutrient deficiencies and excesses related to a variety of diseases - depends on consumption of a wide diversity of foods, including whole grains, legumes, nuts, fruits, vegetables, animal products, roots, and tubers. Notably, one of the key indicators of food security is the availability and accessibility of diversified food sources by individuals to meet their nutritional dietary requirements and enhance their healthy wellbeing (FAO; Chivenge et al, 2015). More recently, breeding of highly nutritious traditional, indigenous, and orphan crops has received increased attention. Some of the most micronutrient and protein-rich crops, like legumes, seeds, fruits, and vegetables, receive little-to-no breeding research and investment, but a diet incorporating a variety of NUCS offers improved nutrition and overall health, while also providing extra advantages for human productivity and livelihoods. This has led to heavy dependency on a few crops, lack of resilience in food systems, and an increase in dependency on commodity crops, as well as malnutrition and undernutrition.
