AU  - Pesala Busenna, Pesala Busenna
TI  - Agricultural wells in rural India: a case study of Ungaranigundla village, Kurnool District of Andhra Pradesh.
T2  - Agricultural Situation in India
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Agricultural sector plays a main role in Andhra Pradesh and also ground water plays a pivotal role in agricultural production. The total net area irrigated by wells and tube wells together accounted for 26.44 lakh hectares in 2012-13 in Andhra Pradesh. Most of India's geographical area is very suitable for cultivation, but there is water scarcity. Due to this reason farmers drill bore wells in their lands. The diameter/perimeter details were collected through Global Positioning System(GPS) and maps drawn through Geographical Information System (GIS). The major findings of the study are: A majority of the households are small and marginal farmers and land less laborers. Most of the SCs do not have economic assets, particularly land and bore wells. Ungaranigundla village farmers drill bore wells to a depth of 100 metres for getting water. The study reveals that most of the advanced farmers dig more bore wells to a greater depth also. Investment on bore wells is not useful for farmers due to the failure of bore wells digging and also because that area cannot be used for cultivation.
