TY  - JOUR
AU  - Abdalla, Ahmed
AU  - Kalkum, Miriam
TI  - Building climate-resilient landscapes in Ethiopia's lowlands.
T2  - Rural 21
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This article discusses the challenges faced by agro-pastoralists in the arid and semi-arid lowlands of Ethiopia due to climate change, including longer droughts, increased floods, and overexploited natural resources. It highlights the Dry Valley Rehabilitation and Productive Use (DVRPU) approach, which aims to enhance drought resilience through measures such as water-spreading weirs, dry-stone measures, and gabions. The approach involves a seven-step process, from satellite identification to productive use, and has led to substantial biomass and grain production, reduced soil erosion, and improved livelihoods. The socio-economic impacts include increased food security, economic diversification, and reduced out-migration. Environmental benefits include enhanced soil moisture, carbon sequestration, and groundwater replenishment. The article concludes that DVRPU is a cost-effective and scalable solution for similar landscapes in the Horn of Africa.
