AU  - Abay, Kibrom A.
AU  - Koru, Bethelhem
AU  - Chamberlin, Jordan
AU  - Berhane, Guush
TI  - Does rainfall variability explain low uptake of agricultural credit? Evidence from Ethiopia.
T2  - European Review of Agricultural Economics
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Credit markets are key instruments by which liquidity-constrained smallholder farmers may finance productive investments. However, the documented low demand and uptake of agricultural credit by smallholder farmers in sub-Saharan Africa pose challenges for energizing rural transformation in the region. In this paper, the researchers investigate the impact of rainfall uncertainty-a major source of production risk-on the uptake of credit by rural farm households in Ethiopia. The researchers further examine whether rainfall uncertainty explains credit rationing among those households not participating in rural credit markets. The researchers find that rainfall variability discourages the uptake of agricultural credit. The researchers also find that rainfall variability is associated with credit risk rationing, expressed as low demand for agricultural credit. The researchers show that our findings are robust to alternative ways of constructing rainfall variability (inter-annual or inter-seasonal) and a battery of robustness checks. For instance, the researchers show that rainfall variability is a strong predictor of credit uptake in rural areas while less relevant in urban areas. The researchers also document heterogeneous responses to rainfall variability; those households living in the arid and semi-arid lands of Ethiopia, which are believed to be more vulnerable to recurrent weather shocks, are more responsive to rainfall variability in terms of reduced uptake of agricultural credit. Our results highlight the impacts of uninsured production risk on the demand for agricultural credit and hence smallholder agricultural investments. Our findings suggest the importance of interventions aimed at relaxing smallholders' credit rationing while also reducing their production risk.
