TY  - JOUR
AU  - Basu, R. N.
TI  - Global climate change vis-a-visagriculture and food security.
T2  - SATSA Mukhaptra Annual Technical Issue
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Climate change is a complex, important and often controversial issue. A clear understanding of the causative factors behind this is necessary to visualize its impact on agriculture since the present-day industrial-agricultural system has been responsible for about one-third of the anthropogenic greenhouse gas emissions, causing global warming. Extreme events such as floods, droughts and tropical cyclones are presently more intense than before, and such events are associated with significant adverse consequences on food and forestry production, and very often with food insecurity. I lence, there is a need to shift from defining the climate threat to seek appropriate solutions for addressing the impending challenges. Agricultural policies need also to be developed for emission reduction (mitigation) as well as adaptation to climate change. Scientific evidence about the seriousness of the threat to agriculture, food and water security, and the loss of livelihoods is ambiguous, and the exact magnitude is uncertain because of the complex interactions and feedback processes in the ecosystem and economy. The present paper deals with the climate change-agriculture interface, salient features of climate change scenario, and relevant features of conventional (industrial) and holistic eco-sustainable farming systems. A broad idea about the general environmental and agricultural issues and their socioeconomic implications on livelihood security of small and marginal farmers of developing countries, in general, and of India, in particular, has also been depicted.
