TI  - PMK(R)3 - an early-maturing, drought-tolerant rice variety for Tamil Nadu, India.
T2  - International Rice Research Notes
M3  - Journal article
AB  - PMK(R)3 is an early-maturing (107-118 d) rice cultivar developed at TNAU (Tamil Nadu, India) derived from UPLRi/CO 43. It has recorded a mean grain yield of 3.0 t/ha from 83 trials conducted across years and locations, with a 13 and 17% yield increase over local drought-tolerant control cultivars PMK 2 and TKM 11, respectively. This semidwarf (100-110 cm), nonlodging cultivar is ideal for areas where there is occasional flooding during the later phase of crop growth. It tolerates leaf blast [Magnaporthe grisea] and sheath rot [Sarocladium oryzae] under field conditions and is resistant to whitebacked planthopper [Sogatella furcifera] under laboratory conditions. It also has higher field tolerance for leaffolders [Pyralidae] and stem borers than the local control PMK 2. PMK(R)3 was found to be highly suitable for cultivation by Tamil Nadu's resource-poor farmers.
