AU  - Nkwanda, P.
AU  - Njobvu, T. D.
AU  - Kapondamgaga, P.
TI  - Suitability of small-scale fish farming for improved livelihoods in Traditional Authority Kachere, Dedza district, central Malawi.
T2  - Malawi Journal of Agricultural Sciences
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Physical and socio-economic factors were assessed to determine if the area under Traditional Authority (TA) Kachere in Dedza district in Malawi was suitable for fish farming. Physical factors were initially deduced from a 1:50,000 topographic scale map and validated through a reconnaissance survey and soil analytical data. Socio-economic factors, were investigated using a structured questionnaire to 180 respondents from 17 villages. Focus group discussions were held with about 20 farmers in Kadzombe and Kadzinja villages. Based on soil texture, water availability, pattern of flooding, terrain, proximity to settlement, accessibility, land tenure system, presence of fish ponds and/or reservoirs, and rice fields, six out of nine Village Development Committees (VDCs) were selected as suitable for fish farming. The majority of the respondents (>98%) were subsistence farmers. Results showed that Irish potato gave the highest gross margins (MK 42, 598 ha-1year-1), whereas maize gave the lowest (MK 1,812 ha-1year-1). On the other hand, projections from a 400 m2fish pond indicated a profit margin of MK 39,410 year-1, which is second to Irish potatoes. Farmers spent more time working in dimbas which are preferred to circumvent dry season droughts, suggesting that these farmers would easily take care of their fish ponds if these were constructed along dambo margins. Although only six farmers had practiced fish farming, the majority of the respondents were willing to start fish farming. About 69% of the respondents stated that they had not started fish farming because of lack of knowledge resulting from inadequate awareness programs and lack of training. Overall, the results from this study showed that fish farming was possible, and had potential to improve the livelihoods of rural communities through enhanced incomes and improved nutrition.
