TI  - A sustainable approach to increased soybean production in western Kenya.
T2  - 10th African Crop Science Conference Proceedings, Maputo, Mozambique, 10-13 October 2011
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - Soybean (Glycine max(L.) Merril) is ranked as the number two oil crop in Kenya. It is a multipurpose crop, ideal for human and livestock feeding and for sustainable cereal production. Yields under Kenyan conditions are low yet appropriate soybean technologies are available for immediate adoption by farmers. The objective of this study was to screen local and exotic soybean varieties, for tolerance to drought, biomass production, seed yield and promiscuity. The paper reports on soybean variety adaptation, farmer participatory variety evaluation (FPVS) and variety preference by gender in five districts in Western Kenya (Migori, Busia, Teso, Mumias and Butere). The design of the "baby trials" was multi-locational, each site had 15 varieties, fitted in a total area of 5*5*15 m2=375 m2with three checks. Farmers had a total of 24 criteria for evaluation on a scale of 1 to 10. Some lines were found to be superior to the commercial varieties. Across gender and location, the most important criteria used in evaluating the improved soybean varieties were number of pods and the maturity period. Male farmers preferred large-sized grains for marketability and high market prices, while female farmers preferred varieties which mature early and cook faster. Some varieties were acceptable in certain locations and rejected in others. In order to avoid the risk of low adoption, FPVS is recommended. From the analysis DPSB 19 (TGX1740-2F) is the only variety that can be recommended across locations. Late maturing promiscuous varieties produce huge biomass, but their grain yield is low as compared to early maturing varieties. Farmers prefer early maturing varieties to escape drought.
