AU  - Amaruzaman, S.
AU  - Lusiana, B.
AU  - Leimona, B.
TI  - System vulnerabilities and farmer's preferences in Buol district, Indonesia.
T2  - ICRAF Working Paper - World Agroforestry Centre
M3  - Bulletin
AB  - The majority of residents of Buol District in Central Sulawesi Province, Indonesia depend on agriculture for their livelihood. Just as in other relatively disadvantaged districts in Indonesia, small farmers in Buol are vulnerable to shocks and changes, whether associated with climate change or socio-economic-political change. Various programs have been undertaken by government agencies and non-governmental organizations to improve the resilience of small farmers to shocks and change. In this research, the perception of the vulnerability of male and female farmers in Buol was analyzed. Identified vulnerabilities include "commodity productivity fluctuations" as well as "shocks, exposure, response and impact" (SERI) that are natural and caused by extreme events. To determine the potential for increased resilience of small farmers through agricultural activities, this study discusses the criteria that farmers consider when choosing trees and plants, as well as the preferences of tree and plant types based on these criteria. Research was conducted in three climate-smart, tree-based, co-investment in project locations Adaptation and Mitigation in Asia (Smart Tree-Invest Project) in Buol District, Central Sulawesi, Indonesia. Vulnerability assessment was conducted using a focus group discussion approach (FGD), while tree and plant selection preferences were analyzed using Analytical Hierarchical Methodology (AHP). People in the Upper DAS Area state the scarcity of water is one of the main problems due to the absence of technical irrigation systems in their area, so they are very dependent on rainfall. In the Central DAS area, communities consider flooding a problem which began to occur after construction of the dam that changed the direction of river flow. Farmers in the coastal zone face the threat of coastal erosion due to mangrove degradation. Related fluctuations in coconut productivity are considered the most resilient to extreme events. While cocoa is considered the most vulnerable commodity, because productivity fluctuates over the years during extreme events. Both male and female farmers choose three of the highest priority criteria in terms of tree selection and crops: land suitability; household income; and ease of care. These criteria were selected by all groups in all regions. The five main commodities that farmers prioritize in all areas were cocoa, coconut, rice, cloves and coffee. On any farming issues identified, the farming community has taken various action responses, as well as considering potential solutions to the problems at hand. Recognizing the main problems and the ideal response based on the perspective of farmers is very important in order to provide effective solutions within increased resilience of farmers in the region.
