TI  - Cane energy for sustainable development and economic competitiveness in Southern Africa.
T2  - XXVI Congress, International Society of Sugar Cane Technologists, ICC, Durban, South Africa, 29 July - 2 August, 2007
M3  - Book chapter
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - This article summarizes the work of the Cane Resources Network for Southern Africa (CARENSA), a four-year North-South-South policy-oriented research network, focusing on how bio-energy from sugarcane can support sustainable development and improve global competitiveness in southern Africa. The approach included a synthesis of existing research, review of industry practices, development of performance benchmarks, analysis of market scenarios for biomass resources from sugarcane, and an environmental assessment. Stakeholder meetings, technical exchanges, and workshops facilitated collaboration across disciplines, professions, and economic sectors. The work program included five areas of analysis: agriculture, industry, markets, impacts, and integration. A detailed GIS analysis of the potential for sugarcane showed significant potential for expanded cane production in Malawi, Mozambique, and Zambia. Alternative scenarios in the SADC region for ethanol production and bagasse cogeneration were identified. The environmental impacts are likely to become serious only where water scarcity is present and/or where local pollution regulations are poorly developed or enforced. Socio-economic impacts would include the creation of significant new livelihoods, although small-scale farmers would need some technical assistance in order to develop marketable product portfolios. The future competitiveness of the sugar industry can be improved through renewable energy markets for ethanol and co-generated electricity, while the success of renewable energy markets will in turn require regional coordination strategies. A reduction in SADC sugar exports can be compensated by adding value from ethanol and co-generated electricity. The goal of sustainable development within SADC can be furthered through progressive policies that include economic incentives to stimulate innovative applications and new markets for cane resources.
