AU  - ,
TI  - Nepal: flood impact assessment: DIEM-impact report, November 2024.
T2  - Nepal: flood impact assessment - DIEM-Impact report, November 2024
M3  - Reports
AB  - The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) launched a Data in Emergencies Impact (DIEM-Impact) assessment in the aftermath of the September 2024 floods in Nepal. The floods had a catastrophic impact on agricultural production in the area targeted by the assessment. Ninety-eight percent of rice farmers reported flood damage during critical harvesting periods, leading to severe losses, with 68 percent of farmers experiencing very severe damage. The estimated value of damages was USD 4.7 million, with rice paddies alone estimated to have suffered USD 4.2 million in losses. Total estimated losses amounted to USD 4.4 million, with USD 4.2 million attributed to lost income from crop sales or consumption. Wealthier households experienced greater absolute losses in assets and livestock, but the least well-off households faced near-complete depletion, increasing vulnerability to long-term poverty. Twenty-seven percent of households were unable to farm or farm as usual, with this proportion being higher among less well-off households and small-scale farmers. Food security indicators showed significant stress, with moderate to severe recent food insecurity linked to asset depletion and losses in cereal production and livestock. Households solely engaged in crop production were the most food insecure, while those involved in livestock faced significant asset depletion, compounding food insecurity. Critical infrastructure loss, such as irrigation systems and animal shelters, further hindered recovery. Immediate relief, recovery, and agricultural support are necessary to restore livelihoods and repair critical infrastructure.
